`extern "C"` bridge over `gdextension_interface.h` (ADR-0011 §D1/D3).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
NVIDIA CUDA runtime — NOT bundled
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This package (vokra-godot) does NOT bundle NVIDIA CUDA runtime
libraries (cudart, cudnn, cublas, nvrtc, or the CUDA driver itself).

When CUDA acceleration is enabled at runtime, Vokra dynamically loads
the system-installed CUDA driver via:

  * dlopen("libcuda.so")  on Linux
  * LoadLibrary("nvcuda.dll")  on Windows

and dynamically loads the system-installed NVRTC via the equivalent
Driver API entry points. Vokra does not link against cudart_static and
does not ship any file named cudart*, cudnn*, cublas*, or nvcuda*.

This satisfies the NVIDIA CUDA EULA requirement that runtime
redistributables be "installed only in a private (non-shared) directory
location" — a constraint incompatible with Godot AssetLib distribution,
which places the GDExtension shared library in a shared `addons/vokra/`
directory under each consumer project.

Consumers requiring CUDA acceleration MUST install the NVIDIA CUDA
Toolkit separately per NVIDIA's terms. Absence of a system CUDA install
means the CUDA backend is unavailable; Vokra does NOT silently fall
back to CPU (FR-EX-08) — an explicit error surfaces through
`vokra_last_error()` and reaches GDScript as a `VokraError` value.

CI enforcement: scripts/compliance/check-godot-package-no-nvidia.sh
runs on every release, scanning `addons/vokra/bin/**` for banned
filenames (both `cudart*` and `libcudart*` forms — the Unity mirror's
`cudart*` glob alone would miss Linux `libcudart.so.12`), inspecting
each shipped .dll / .so / .dylib for undefined-symbol references to
cudart / cudnn / cublasLt, and validating LICENSE + NOTICE +
vokra.gdextension presence. Any hit fails the release job.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Third-party attributions
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This package embeds the Vokra native runtime (vokra-capi cdylib), which
is written from scratch in Rust and licensed Apache-2.0 in lock-step
with the workspace-wide policy. Attributions for upstream research
weights and datasets consumed by Vokra models (Silero VAD, Whisper,
piper-plus, CAM++, Kokoro-82M, Mimi codec, etc.) are recorded in
docs/license-audit.md and the root-level NOTICE file in the main Vokra
repository (https://github.com/ayutaz/vokra).

The Godot binding does not add any new third-party runtime dependency
beyond what the main Vokra runtime already consumes — Cargo.lock for
the vokra-godot crate contains only first-party `vokra-*` crates
(zero-dep invariant NFR-DS-02 preserved even in this isolated
workspace).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Demo weights — MIT-only (fetch-demo-models.sh)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The demo weight downloader shipped alongside this package
(`addons/vokra/fetch-demo-models.sh`) fetches MIT-licensed models only:
Silero VAD v5 (MIT), Whisper base (MIT), piper-plus voices (MIT).

CC-BY-NC / CC-BY-NC-SA / non-commercial weights (F5-TTS, Fish-Speech,
Bark, EnCodec) are excluded from the official model zoo per the M2-13
compliance gate — the AssetLib channel is MIT-only by policy (BR-10 /
FR-OP-32).

Voice-clone models (RVC, GPT-SoVITS) are categorically banned from
Vokra core per BR-08 (Tennessee ELVIS Act + federal NO FAKES Act
compatibility) and are not exposed through the AssetLib package.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Watermark / AI-generated audio disclosure (EU AI Act §50, SB 942)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

TTS output produced through this package is subject to Vokra's
`WatermarkConfig` API in the main Vokra runtime. The watermark
embedding path is `deferred` for the current release train (see the
root NOTICE §5 attribution for the Mimi codec attribution note and
docs/legal-compliance.md for the EU AI Act §50 / California SB 942
policy status). Consumers integrating Vokra TTS in the EU or California
market are responsible for meeting the applicable disclosure
obligations.

